{
  "task": "transcribe",
  "language": "english",
  "duration": 102.62999725341797,
  "text": "Mandarin is a broken language, and you can hear it in every pop song. It wasn't always this way. Rewind to the Tang Dynasty, China's golden age of poetry. Back then, the language had roughly three to four times as many distinct syllables as Mandarin does now, and words ended in crisp, hard consonants. P, T, K, and M. Take the word for moon. In Tang Chinese, it sounded like this. Nenguat, a hard stop, right on that T. Now fast forward to Mandarin. That same word, Yue, the hard ending, gone. And it isn't just this one word. Ten, S-A-P to she, six, L-U-K to L-I, heart, S-A-M to X-1-N. Every one of those final consonants, P, T, K, M, vanished from Mandarin completely. The result? A language of 1.4 billion people running on only about 400 syllables. And when you cram that many words into so few sounds, the rhyme pool collapses. Everything starts to sound the same. That's why so much Mandarin pop leans on long, open vowels. Ah, I, O, Wei. There are no crisp endings left to snap a line shut. But head south, to Hong Kong and Guangdong, and you hit the language that kept everything. Cantonese still has six tones, and every one of those old endings, P, T, K, M, fully intact, which leads to something wild. Thousand-year-old Tang poems, the ones that sound slightly off in Mandarin, still rhyme perfectly in Cantonese. The southern dialect is basically a time capsule of how this poetry was meant to sound. So here's the irony. Mandarin won. It became the voice of a nation. But while the language won, the sound was lost. Want more about the languages hiding in plain sight? Follow Stack Tags.",
